1. The "Network Glitch Art" Generator
Instead of writing a complex Python proxy, we can use Linux's built-in Traffic Control (tc) system. This script tells the Squirrel's networking kernel to intentionally introduce microscopic data corruption (flipping random bits) in the packets passing through it. When downloading unencrypted media or loading certain data streams, this forces the receiving computer to render the corrupted bytes, creating beautiful, unpredictable visual glitches.

Bash
#!/bin/bash
# Title:        Network Glitch Art
# Description:  Intentionally corrupts 1% of network traffic to generate digital art.
# Net Mode:     BRIDGE

function run_glitch_art() {
    NETMODE BRIDGE
    sleep 10
    
    # Indicate armed state
    LED SETUP
    
    # Wait for the button press to start the glitching
    NO_LED=true BUTTON
    
    # Indicate the art generator is active (Blinking Purple)
    LED M FAST
    
    # Flush any existing traffic control rules on the bridge
    tc qdisc del dev br-lan root 2>/dev/null
    
    # The Magic: Introduce exactly 1% packet corruption
    tc qdisc add dev br-lan root netem corrupt 1%
    
    # Wait for the second button press to stop
    NO_LED=true BUTTON
    
    # Clean up the rules to restore normal internet
    tc qdisc del dev br-lan root 2>/dev/null
    LED G SUCCESS
}

USB_WAIT
run_glitch_art &
wait
Note: Because modern web traffic is heavily encrypted (HTTPS), corrupted packets are usually just dropped and re-requested. This payload works best when browsing HTTP sites, playing older LAN games, or pulling raw video streams over UDP.

2. The LAN Party "Chaos Engine"
